Prof. dr hab. '''Bogumi≈Ç Andrzej Grott''' (IPA: [b…îÀà…°umiw Ààand. ê…õj Àà…°…æ…îtÃ™]) (born 1940) is a [[Poland|Polish]] historian, lecturer and professor at the Institute of [[religious studies|Religious Studies]] of [[Jagiellonian University]] in [[Krak√≥w]]. He specializes in the history of Polish political thought, especially nationalism and its connection with [[Roman Catholicism|Catholicism]], right-wing [[National Democracy]] political camp, and [[Polish-Ukrainian relations]].
Grott published about 135 publications, with 80 scientific articles in [[Polish language|Polish]], [[German language|German]] and [[Ukrainian language|Ukrainian]]. He received his [[doctoral degree]] in 1975, [[habilitation]] in 1985 and a professor degree in 1997.
Grott has also written essays and articles published in Polish nationalist and radical Catholic press such as the ''[[Nasz Dziennik]]''.<ref>[http://www.radiomaryja.pl/artykuly.php?id=99678 Bogumil Grott. ''Co powinni≈õmy wiedzieƒá o nacjonalizmie ukrai≈Ñskim ''.] Nasz Dziennik, 2009-07-06</ref><ref>Marcin Starnawski. (2003). [http://www.tandfonline.com/doi/abs/10.1080/0031322022000054349#preview Nationalist discourse and the ultra-conservative press in contemporary Poland: a case study of Nasz Dziennik]. ''Patterns of Prejudice ''. (37): pp. 65-81.</ref>
In 2008 he also signed a letter accusing the [[University of Wroc≈Çaw]] of practicing "Stalinism" when the university, and more liberal media such as ''[[Gazeta Wyborcza]]'', criticized some figures, such as [[Jerzy Robert Nowak]], at an academic conference concerning Polish-German and Polish-Russian relations. Grott and other academic figures accused the university of censorship.<ref>[http://www.naszdziennik.pl/index.php?dat=20081220&typ=po&id=po61.txt W obronie wolno≈õci nauki] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120331131010/http://www.naszdziennik.pl/index.php?dat=20081220&typ=po&id=po61.txt |date=March 31, 2012 }} December 15, 2008. Published in Nasz Dziennik 20‚Äì21 December 2008, Nr 297</ref>
