{{Use mdy dates|date=May 2016}} {{Use American English|date=May 2016}} {{Infobox person | name = Georg Iggers | image = | caption = | birth_date = {{birth date|1926|12|07}} | birth_place = [[Hamburg]], Germany | death_date = {{death date and age|2017|11|26|1926|12|07}} | death_place = [[Buffalo, New York]], United States | residence = | nationality = | other_names = | known_for = | occupation = Historian }}
'''Georg G. Iggers''' (December 7, 1926 ‚Äì November 26, 2017) was an American historian of modern Europe, [[historiography]], and European intellectual history.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Daum|first=Andreas W|date=|title=Georg G. Iggers (1926-2017)|url=|journal=Central European History|volume=51|pages=335-353|via=}}</ref>
Iggers was born in [[Hamburg]], [[Germany]], in 1926. Being a [[German Jew]] he fled Germany with his family to the US in 1938, only few weeks before the [[Kristallnacht]].<ref>[http://www.buffalo.edu/ubreporter/archive/vol37/vol37n19/articles/Iggers.html "Scholars take active role in history"] UB reporter</ref> Iggers belonged to the young √©migr√©s from the Third Reich who later in life, as academic scholars in the United States, had a decisive impact on reviewing critically the history of Germany.<ref>{{Cite book|title=The Second Generation: √âmigr√©s from Nazi Germany as Historians|last=Daum|first=Andreas W., Hartmut Lehmann, and James J. Sheehan, eds.|publisher=Berghahn|year=2016|isbn=978-1-78238-985-9|location=New York|pages=}}</ref>
He was Distinguished Professor Emeritus at [[University of Buffalo]] and 2007 recipient of the First Class Cross of the [[Order of Merit of the Federal Republic of Germany]]. Iggers received the [[Humboldt Prize]], honorary doctorate degrees from the [[University of Richmond]], [[Technische Universit√§t Darmstadt]], and [[Philander Smith College]], and fellowships from the [[American Philosophical Society]], [[Fulbright Foundation]], [[John Simon Guggenheim Memorial Foundation|Guggenheim Foundation]], [[National Endowment for the Humanities]], and [[Rockefeller Foundation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.history.buffalo.edu/people/iggers.shtml |title=Georg G. Iggers, Department of History, University at Buffalo |date=May 23, 2015 |publisher= |deadurl=unfit |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150523014001/http://www.history.buffalo.edu/people/iggers.shtml |archivedate=May 23, 2015 }}</ref>
He was especially noted for his writings on historiography.
He died on November 26, 2017, of complications from a [[cerebral hemorrhage]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/11/26/georg-g-iggers-renowned-historian-and-civil-rights-activist/|title=Georg G. Iggers, renowned historian and civil rights activist|date=2017-11-26|work=The Buffalo News|access-date=2017-11-27|language=en-US}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://buffalonews.com/2017/11/27/iggers-dr-georg/|title=Iggers, Dr. Georg|last=|first=|date=2017-11-27|work=The Buffalo News|access-date=2017-11-27|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|language=en-US}}</ref>
