{{Moroccan literature}} '''Ab≈´ al-Hassan ‚ÄòAlƒ´ ibn Abƒ´ Zar‚Äò al-FƒÅsƒ´''' ({{lang-ar|ÿ£ÿ®Ÿà ÿßŸÑÿ≠ÿ≥ŸÜ ÿπŸÑŸä ÿ®ŸÜ ÿ£ÿ®Ÿä ÿ≤ÿ±ÿπ ÿßŸÑŸÅÿßÿ≥Ÿä}}) (d. between 1310 and 1320) is the commonly presumed original author of the popular and influential medieval history of [[Morocco]] known as ''[[Rawd al-Qirtas]]'',<ref>''Encyclopedia of Arabic literature: A-J'', Vol.1, Ed. Julie Scott Meisami and Paul Starkey, (Routledge, 1998), 307.</ref> said to have been written at the instigation of [[Marinid]] Sultan [[Abu Sa'id Uthman II]]. His full [[Arabic name#Nasab|nasab]] is sometimes given as ''ibn Abd Allah ibn Abi Zar'' and sometimes as ''ibn Muhammad ibn Ahmad ibn Umar ibn Abi Zar''. The uncertainty about his name and authorship of the [[Rawd al-Qirtas|Rawd]] is caused by the many variant manuscripts in circulation since the Middle Ages. Very little is known about his life except that he was evidently a scholar at [[Fes]].
