{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}} {{Use dmy dates|date=October 2013}} {{Infobox terrorist attack |title=Inglis barracks bombing |image=Inglis Barracks.jpg |caption = Officers Mess |partof = [[The Troubles]] |location=Inglis barracks, [[Mill Hill]], [[London]], NW7 [[England]] |coordinates = {{coord |51|12|49|N|1|24|0|E|region:GB_type:event|display=inline,title}} |target=British soldiers |date=1 August 1988 |time=08:22 |timezone=[[GMT]] |type=[[Time bomb]] |fatalities=1 British soldier |injuries=9 British soldiers |perp=[[Provisional Irish Republican Army|Provisional IRA]] }}
{{Campaignbox Northern Ireland Troubles}}
The '''Inglis Barracks bombing''' was a bomb attack carried out by the [[Provisional Irish Republican Army]] (PIRA) on 1 August 1988 on a [[British Army]] barracks called [[Inglis Barracks]] in [[Mill Hill]], [[London]]. The attack killed one soldier from the [[Royal Engineers]], injured nine more and destroyed large parts of the barracks.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch88.htm#Aug|title=CAIN: Chronology of the Conflict 1988|first=Dr Martin|last=Melaugh|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> It was the first IRA attack in England since the [[Brighton hotel bombing|1984 Brighton Bombing]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/cgi-bin/dyndeaths.pl?querytype=date&day=12&month=10&year=1984|title=CAIN: Sutton Index of Deaths|first=Malcolm|last=Sutton|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref>
==Background== The Provisional IRA had carried out sustained bombing campaigns in England before, between 1973 and 1976<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch73.htm#Mar|title=CAIN: Chronology of the Conflict 1973|first=Dr Martin|last=Melaugh|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/othelem/chron/ch75.htm#Dec|title=CAIN: Chronology of the Conflict 1975|first=Dr Martin|last=Melaugh|website=Cain.ulst.ac.uk|accessdate=4 August 2017}}</ref> carrying out hundreds of bombings in the process killing over 60 people and injuring over 1,000. The IRA carried out sporadic attacks in England between 1977 and 1984. The bombing at Inglis barracks commenced a new sustained bombing campaign that would last until the 1994 IRA ceasefire.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-northern-ireland-28957532|title='It's Over': Reporting the IRA ceasefire 20 years ago|publisher=BBC|date=27 August 2014|accessdate=18 May 2018}}</ref>
==Bombing== The living quarters of the barracks were demolished by the blast.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1988-08-01/news/mn-5021_1_ira-bomb|title=IRA Bomb Hits Barracks in London; 1 Dead|last=Reuters|date=1988-08-01|work=Los Angeles Times|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en-US|issn=0458-3035}}</ref> Construction worker Frank McParland, who was working inside the barracks, said the middle section was obliterated. The roof of the two-story red brick building was blown off.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1988/08/02/world/ira-bombing-in-london-kills-1-british-soldier-and-wounds-10.html|title=I.R.A. Bombing in London Kills 1 British Soldier and Wounds 10|last=Times|first=Bernard Weinraub and Special To the New York|access-date=2018-05-15|language=en}}</ref> Corporal Ian Booth was rescued alive after he was trapped beneath the debris. He was saved by a radiator that fell across him and shielded him from falling masonry. Fires raged for three hours as rescuers pulled the injured from heaps of rubble and smoldering timber. Half of the barracks, the army's main postal depot in the capital, used to lie in then [[Prime Minister]] [[Margaret Thatcher]]'s [[Finchley (UK Parliament constituency)|Finchley constituency]].<ref>''Boundaries of Parliamentary Constituencies 1885‚Äì1972'', compiled and edited by F.W.S. Craig (Parliamentary Reference Publications 1972)</ref>
The IRA issued a statement the next day in London and Dublin claiming responsibility for the bombing and said more attacks in England would follow.
