{{Infobox writer | name = Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski | image = Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski - Biedni Polacy (cover).jpg | imagesize = 180px | caption = Front cover of ''Biedni Polacy patrzƒÖ na getto'' (the Misfortunate Poles look at the Ghetto) by Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski, {{ISBN|978-83-08-042-01-4}} | pseudonym = | birth_date = {{birth date |1931|01|15|df=y}} | birth_place = [[Warsaw]], [[Second Polish Republic|Poland]] | death_date = {{Death date and age|2009|02|10|1931|01|15|df=yes}} | death_place = [[Krak√≥w]] | occupation = Writer, academic | nationality = Polish | citizenship = Polish | period = | genre = | notableworks = | influences = | influenced = | website = }} '''Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski''' (15 January 1931 &ndash; 10 February 2009) was a Polish historian, literary critic, publicist and translator. He was a leading representative of the [[Krak√≥w]] school of literary criticism, regarded as one of the most influential critics of postwar [[Poland]].
Professor of the [[Jagiellonian University]], B≈Ço≈Ñski was habilitated there for the work entitled ''[[Miko≈Çaj Sƒôp Szarzy≈Ñski]] and the beginnings of the [[Polish Baroque]].'' He was the literary editor for the publication of [[Witold Gombrowicz]]'s collected works in 1986‚Äì88 through ''[[Wydawnictwo Literackie]]''. He was also the Fellow of [[Collegium Invisibile]]. In 1996‚Äì2001 he served as juror for the [[Nike Award|Nike Literary Award]]. In November 1995 he was awarded the Krak√≥w Book of the Month Award for the collected works of [[S≈Çawomir Mro≈ºek]], his long-time friend from the [[History of Poland (1945‚Äì1989)#Stalinist era (1948‚Äì1956)|Stalinist period]].<ref name="ci.edu.pl">{{cite web |url=http://www.ci.edu.pl/index.php?id=tutorzy&kat=Czlonkowie |title=List of Fellows |publisher=Collegium Invisible ''ci.edu.pl'', Warsaw |accessdate=25 April 2011}}</ref>
==Biography== Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski was born in [[Warsaw]] in 1931. During the [[occupation of Poland]] by Nazi Germany, he witnessed the liquidation of the [[Warsaw Ghetto]] in 1942 when some 300,000 Jews were sent to [[Treblinka]] and exterminated in a [[Grossaktion Warsaw (1942)|single classified operation]].<ref name="ushmm.org-uprising">United States Holocaust Memorial Museum, [http://www.ushmm.org/wlc/article.php?ModuleId=10005188 Warsaw Ghetto Uprising.] {{nobreak|Retrieved March 6, 2013.}}</ref> B≈Ço≈Ñski later wrote that a Jewish boy who escaped, run into him on the street but he didn't help, which many years later brought about a deep feeling of guilt, and inspired his best-known piece of writing published by ''[[Tygodnik Powszechny]]'' in 1987 under the Polish title "Biedni Polacy patrzƒÖ na getto" (the Poor Poles look at the Ghetto) invariably undermining the historical significance of the [[rescue of Jews by Poles during the Holocaust]].<ref name="tp-blonski">{{cite web|url=http://tygodnik.onet.pl/30,0,21303,artykul.html |title=Biedni Polacy patrzƒÖ na getto |publisher=''[[Tygodnik Powszechny]]'' |author=Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski |accessdate=March 6, 2013 |format=Internet Archive |pages=7 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090214135615/http://tygodnik.onet.pl/30%2C0%2C21303%2Cartykul.html |archivedate=February 14, 2009 |df= }}</ref>
B≈Ço≈Ñski finished his [[Polish studies]] at the Jagiellonian University in 1952 during the darkest years of [[History of Poland (1945‚Äì89)#Stalinist era (1948‚Äì1956)|Stalinist terror]] in Poland.<ref name="uj.edu.pl"/> In 1953, he participated in the defamation of Catholic priests from Krak√≥w, three of whom were condemned to death by the Communist government during the [[Stalinist show trial of the Krak√≥w Curia]] ‚Äì he was one of several signatories of an [[open letter]] from ZLP to Polish authorities supporting the persecution of Catholic religious leaders groundlessly accused of treason and imprisoned by the [[Ministry of Public Security (Poland)|Ministry of Public Security]] ‚Äì their death sentences were not enforced although Father J√≥zef Fudali died in unexplained circumstances while in prison.<ref name="IPN-Fudali">{{cite web|url=http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/wystawy/proces_kurii_krakowskiej/html/plansza04f.html |title=Ks. J√≥zef Fudali (1915‚Äì1955), kap≈Çan Archidiecezji Krakowskiej |accessdate=2011-10-26 |deadurl=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120112232154/http://www.ipn.gov.pl/ftp/wystawy/proces_kurii_krakowskiej/html/plansza04f.html |archivedate=January 12, 2012 |df= }}. ''[[Institute of National Remembrance]]''.</ref><ref name="canadafreepress.com">David Dastych, [http://www.canadafreepress.com/2007/dastych011007.htm "Devil's Choice. High-ranking Communist Agents in the Polish Catholic Church."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070301140104/http://www.canadafreepress.com/2007/dastych011007.htm |date=2007-03-01 }} ''Canada Free Press'' (CFP), 10 January 2007.</ref><ref>Wojciech Czuchnowski ''Blizna. Proces kurii krakowskiej 1953'', Krak√≥w 2003.</ref><ref name="naszawitryna.pl">Dr Stanis≈Çaw Krajski, [http://www.naszawitryna.pl/jedwabne_779.html "Zabiƒá ksiƒô≈ºy."] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110914225245/http://www.naszawitryna.pl/jedwabne_779.html |date=2011-09-14 }} ''Katolicka Gazeta Internetowa'', 2001-12-01.</ref><ref name="polskiejutro.com">Damian Nogajski, [http://www.polskiejutro.com/art.php?p=8644&m=r WINY MA≈ÅE I DU≈ªE ‚Äì CZYLI KTO JEST PASZKWILANTEM.] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120329142820/http://www.polskiejutro.com/art.php?p=8644&m=r |date=2012-03-29 }} ''Polskiejutro.com'', No. 227; 11 September 2006.</ref> B≈Ço≈Ñski obtained a position with the Institute of Literary Studies of the [[Polish Academy of Sciences]] in 1959‚Äì62 (after the [[Polish October]]). From 1970 he was employed at the Jagiellonian University. He was a vice-rector for didactic affairs (1981‚Äì84), director of the Institute of [[Polish Studies]] (1988‚Äì91), director of the Department of the Theatre (1977‚Äì1980) and the Department of the 20th Century Polish Literature (1995‚Äì97). As professor, he also lectured Polish literature at the [[University of Sorbonne]], the [[University of Clermont-Ferrand]] and the [[Paris University]] IV. He died on 10 February 2009 in [[Krak√≥w]].<ref name="uj.edu.pl">{{cite web | url=http://www.uj.edu.pl/documents/10172/1315002/Newsletter37.pdf | title=Prof. Jan B≈Ço≈Ñski | publisher=[[Jagiellonian University]] | work=In memoriam. ''First published in [[Gazeta Wyborcza]] 38/2009'' |date=2009 | accessdate=March 6, 2013 | author=Jerzy Jarzƒôbski | pages=14&ndash;16 | format=PDF |via=direct download 1.03 MB}}</ref>
