'''Pekka Johannes H√§m√§l√§inen''' (born 1967, [[Helsinki]]) is a Finnish professor and author of a multiple prize-winning book, ''The Comanche Empire''.<ref name="yale">[http://yalepress.yale.edu/yupbooks/book.asp?isbn=0300126549 Yale University Press]</ref> Since 2012 he has been the Rhodes Professor of American History at the [[University of Oxford]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.history.ox.ac.uk/people/professor-pekka-hamalainen|title=Professor Pekka H√§m√§l√§inen |publisher=University of Oxford Faculty of History|access-date=9 December 2017}}</ref><ref name=" IEA Nantes">{{cite web|url=https://www.iea-nantes.fr/en/news/pekka-has-been-appointed-to-the-prestigious-rhodes-professorship-of-american-history-at-oxford-university_239|title=Pekka has been appointed|publisher=iea-nantes.fr|accessdate=20 September 2018}}</ref> He was formerly in the History Department at [[University of California at Santa Barbara]].<ref>http://www.history.ucsb.edu/people/person.php?account_id=32</ref>
==Life== H√§m√§l√§inen was born and raised in Helsinki, Finland. It wasn't until high school, and an inspiring teacher, that he realized he actually liked history, his core interest being Native American history. At university H√§m√§l√§inen majored in history and trained to become a secondary history teacher. After finishing his M.A. he began work on his Ph.D., and realized that he wanted to become a professional historian.<ref>"Personal correspondence with Dr. H√§m√§l√§inen." Interview by Dakota Wind. October 31, 2017.</ref>
He graduated from [[University of Helsinki]], with a Ph.D. in 2001. He taught at [[Texas A&M University]] from 2002 to 2004. His work has appeared in the ''American Historical Review'', ''Journal of American History'', ''William and Mary Quarterly'', and the ''Western Historical Quarterly''.<ref>https://www.mcgill.ca/cundillprize/shortlist/biographies/</ref><ref>{{Cite journal | doi = 10.5309/willmaryquar.67.2.173| title = The Politics of Grass: European Expansion, Ecological Change, and Indigenous Power in the Southwest Borderlands| journal = The William and Mary Quarterly| volume = 67| issue = 2| pages = 173| year = 2010}}</ref> He taught in the History Department at [[University of California, Santa Barbara]] before moving to Oxford University.
H√§m√§l√§inen is currently researching and composing a history of the Lak»ü√≥ta beginning in the seventeenth century through the twentieth century.
==Awards== * 2009 [[Bancroft Prize]] * 2008 [[Kate Brocks Bates Award]] * 2009 [[Merle Curti Award]]<ref name="yale" /><ref>http://www.indiancountrytoday.com/national/42146272.html</ref> * 2009 [[Cundill Prize]], runner-up * 2009 [[Caughey Western History Association Prize]]
